<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="517" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,358,889]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,358,385]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Modified from 
<bibRefCitation author="Moron, M. A. &amp; Nogueira, G." box="[458,760,359,386]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" pagination="7 - 22" refId="ref4506" refString="Moron, M. A. &amp; Nogueira, G. (2016) Actualizacion del genero Parabyrsopolis Ohaus (Coleoptera: Melolonthidae: Rutelinae). Boletin de la Sociedad Entomologica Aragonesa, 59, 7 - 22." type="journal article" year="2016">Morón &amp; Nogueira (2016)</bibRefCitation>
(bolded words are new characters). Body length 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1324,1436,359,385]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">20.5–35.0</emphasis>
mm. Color yellowish brown, reddish brown, dark, or black, with metallic cupreus, golden, green or blue iridescence in pronotum, scutellum, abdominal sternites, and sometimes in legs; dorsal vestiture absent; ventral vestiture abundant, long; clypeus sub-hexagonal, with sinuate, convergent margins and apex rounded or truncate (
<figureCitation box="[1343,1431,467,493]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,882,907]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,491,851]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[158,1430,489,857]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Variation in the clypeal outer edge. A, Viridimicus species; B, Parabyrsopolis species. The form of P. moroni is shown in black, to demonstrate the new variation inside the genus (modified from Jameson 1990)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3920567" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3920567/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
, grey lines), 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[287,559,503,529]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">or completely rounded</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[575,663,503,529]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,882,907]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,491,851]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[158,1430,489,857]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Variation in the clypeal outer edge. A, Viridimicus species; B, Parabyrsopolis species. The form of P. moroni is shown in black, to demonstrate the new variation inside the genus (modified from Jameson 1990)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3920567" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3920567/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
, black line); frontoclypeal suture complete, mandibles with external edge recurved, entire; labium with the eternal edge narrowly notched and disk widely concave; antennae with 10 antennomeres; antennal club with three antennomeres; pronotum convex, twice wider than long; 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">disc with medial longitudinal groove</emphasis>
; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[402,1083,610,637]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">basal bead complete, basal angles flattened and reflexed</emphasis>
; prothoracic postcoxal process prominent; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[283,1150,646,673]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">elytral discal submargin bare (epipleural carina may have row of setae)</emphasis>
; abdominal sternites 2–4 with similar length in the middle line; fifth sternite longer.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,358,889]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,438,718,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Taxonomic remarks</emphasis>
. The shape of the clypeus on the new species appears to invalidate that key generic character of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jameson" authorityYear="1990" box="[365,494,755,781]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Viridimicus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[365,494,755,781]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Viridimicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, because the only characters left to distinguish both genera sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Jameson, M. L." pageId="2" pageNumber="517" pagination="167 - 174" refId="ref4424" refString="Jameson, M. L. (1999) A new species of Viridimicus Jameson from Honduras (Scarabaeidae: Rutelinae). The Coleopterists Bulletin, 53, 167 - 174." type="journal article" year="1999">Jameson (1999: 171)</bibRefCitation>
, was the color. With the analysis of specimens from different localities, we propose the new clear and constant characters that reinforce the status of both genera, as shown below with the emendation of the key of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burmeister" authorityYear="1844" box="[1301,1405,827,853]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Areodina">Areodina</taxonomicName>
of 
<bibRefCitation author="Jameson, M. L." box="[151,333,863,889]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" pagination="377 - 422" refId="ref4382" refString="Jameson, M. L. (1990) Revision, phylogeny and biogeography of the genera Parabyrsopolis Ohaus and Viridimicus, new genus (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Rutelinae). The Coleopterists Bulletin, 44, 377 - 422." type="journal article" year="1990">Jameson (1990)</bibRefCitation>
:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,931,1100]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">
9. Pronotum with basal bead incomplete medially; males elytral submargin sparsely setigerous (unless abraded), females mostly glabrous; males metallic green; females metallic green, dark brown, or black. Central Mexico to 
<collectingCountry box="[1154,1250,961,983]" name="Honduras" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Honduras</collectingCountry>
.................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Jameson" authorityName="Jameson" authorityYear="1990" box="[1237,1437,990,1011]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Viridimicus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1237,1347,990,1011]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Viridimicus</emphasis>
Jameson
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,931,1100]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">
– Pronotum with basal bead complete or at most interrupted at medial sulcus only; elytral submargin glabrous; males and females reddish brown, brown, or black. Southeastern 
<collectingRegion box="[668,745,1049,1071]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Arizona</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry box="[757,1002,1049,1071]" name="United States of America" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">United States of America</collectingCountry>
) to central 
<collectingCountry box="[1111,1184,1049,1071]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Mexico</collectingCountry>
..................................................................................................... .. 
<taxonomicName authority="Ohaus" authorityName="Ohaus" authorityYear="1915" box="[1221,1436,1078,1100]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Parabyrsopolis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1221,1369,1078,1099]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Parabyrsopolis</emphasis>
Ohaus
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
